[2]
Date: Wed, 16 Mar 2005
From: Hugh Baker <bakerh@inspection.gc.ca>

Re: Unknown epidemic kills 56 in Angola
---------------------------------------
56 people have died in Angola with similar symptoms in the past 2 weeks. It
begins with fever symptoms for 2 days and then the patient begins to cough
up blood, falls into a coma, and dies within 4 days, he explained.
These are also the symptoms of acute-onset pneumonic plague. The recent
exodus of mine workers from the plague-affected area of the Democratic
Republic of Congo, which borders Angola on the north and east, should be
sufficient to include _Yersinia pestis_ as a differential. The 2 countries
share a major railway connection, the Kwango (Cuango) River and several
highways, facilitating movement of people and rodents between population
centres.
--
Dr. Hugh Baker
Canadian Food Inspection Agency/
Agence canadienne d'inspection des aliments
Toronto, Ontario, Canada
<bakerh@inspection.gc.ca>
[The etiology of this illness is, as yet, undefined. ProMED thanks Dr.
Baker for his comment regarding the possibility of pneumonic plague. -
Mod.LL]
