[3]
Date: 17 Mar 2005
From: ProMED-mail<promed@promedmail.org>
Source: WHO website [edited]
<http://www.who.int/csr/don/2005_03_17b/en/>

>From January to 15 March 2005, 39 deaths from suspected acute haemorrhagic
fever syndrome have been reported to WHO from Uige Province in northern
Angola.
A task force has been put in place at the national level and laboratory
samples have been collected for analysis. The WHO country office is
supporting the Ministry of Health. Active surveillance and retrospective
analysis are in place.
The WHO Regional Office for Africa (AFRO) has alerted members of the AFRO
rapid response network, and staff from the AFRO Inter-country Programme for
Southern Africa are planning to bring supplies of protective equipment for
the investigation and management of suspected cases.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[We await further information on the epidemiologic and laboratory studies,
as well as the age distribution of all reported cases. We do know that the
last 3 deaths have been 2 children and one adult (health care worker).
There was a newswire suggesting that the majority of cases were among
children, with 2 health care workers involved. One wonders if this might be
one of the more "common" culprits discussed in the 1st posting on this
outbreak, such as dengue hemorrhagic fever or yellow fever. Again, this is
not the 1st occurrence of an undiagnosed hemorrhagic fever in Angola, so the
temptation is very strong to speculate that we might be on the verge of
identifying a new or novel virus that produces a hemorrhagic fever syndrome
there.
The addition of pneumonic plague to the differential may be possible, based
on the somewhat sparse clinical descriptions of this outbreak, but the
likelihood of this being related to the ongoing outbreak in the Democratic
Republic of Congo is very low. Geographically the outbreak of pneumonic
plague in the Dem. Rep. of Congo is in the northeast of the country, whereas
the border Angola has with the Dem. Rep. of Congo is in the southwest of the
country. For those of us in North America, it is comparable to the distance
from Montreal to San Diego. - Mod.MPP]
